---
import DocsLayout from '../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro'
import CodeTabs from '../../components/docs/CodeTabs.astro'

const headerCurl = `curl https://api.doc-extraction.com/v1/extractions/123 \\
  -H "Authorization: Bearer dx_live_YOUR_TOKEN_HERE"`

const headerJs = `await fetch('https://api.doc-extraction.com/v1/extractions/123', {
    headers: {
        Authorization: 'Bearer dx_live_YOUR_TOKEN_HERE'
    }
})`

const headerPython = `import requests

requests.get(
    'https://api.doc-extraction.com/v1/extractions/123',
    headers={'Authorization': 'Bearer dx_live_YOUR_TOKEN_HERE'},
)`

const headerGo = `req, _ := http.NewRequest("GET",
    "https://api.doc-extraction.com/v1/extractions/123", nil)
req.Header.Set("Authorization", "Bearer dx_live_YOUR_TOKEN_HERE")`

const headerRuby = `req = Net::HTTP::Get.new(uri)
req['Authorization'] = 'Bearer dx_live_YOUR_TOKEN_HERE'`
---

<DocsLayout
    title="Authentication"
    section="getting-started"
    page="authentication"
>
    <h1>Authentication</h1>
    <p class="lede">
        All authenticated endpoints accept a single bearer token in the
        <code>Authorization</code> header.
    </p>

    <h2>Token format</h2>
    <p>
        DocExtract API tokens are random 256-bit secrets prefixed with
        <code>dx_live_</code>. The full string looks like:
    </p>
    <pre class="not-prose my-4 overflow-x-auto rounded-lg border border-gray-200 bg-gray-50 p-4 font-mono text-[13px] text-gray-900"><code>dx_live_a3f9b2c1d8e74f60a3f9b2c1d8e74f60</code></pre>

    <h2>Sending the token</h2>
    <p>
        Include the token as a bearer credential. We do not accept tokens via
        query string — keeping them out of URLs avoids leakage through proxy
        logs and browser history.
    </p>

    <CodeTabs
        title="Authorization header"
        samples={{
            curl: headerCurl,
            javascript: headerJs,
            python: headerPython,
            go: headerGo,
            ruby: headerRuby
        }}
    />

    <h2>Creating a token</h2>
    <p>
        Tokens are minted from the dashboard at
        <a href="https://app.doc-extraction.com/api-tokens">/api-tokens</a>.
        On creation you can label them (e.g. <em>Production</em>,
        <em>Staging</em>) and pick an optional expiration (30 days, 90 days,
        1 year, or never).
    </p>
    <p>
        <strong>The plaintext is shown exactly once.</strong> After you close
        the creation dialog, only the prefix (<code>dx_live_xxxx…</code>) is
        ever visible in the dashboard. If you lose a token, revoke it and
        create a new one.
    </p>

    <h2>Storing a token securely</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>Treat tokens like passwords — never commit one to a git repo.</li>
        <li>
            Inject via environment variables (<code>DOCEXTRACT_API_TOKEN</code>
            is a fine convention) or a secret manager.
        </li>
        <li>
            Issue a separate token per integration so you can revoke a single
            client without disrupting the rest.
        </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Revoking a token</h2>
    <p>
        Revocation is immediate. From the dashboard, click the trash icon on
        any active token; the next request bearing it will return
        <code>401 Unauthorized</code> with
        <code>"message": "API token revoked"</code>. Audit data
        (<code>last_used_at</code>, total call count, daily usage) survives
        revocation so you can investigate without losing context.
    </p>

    <h2>Expiration</h2>
    <p>
        Tokens with an <code>expires_at</code> set become invalid at that
        instant. Expired requests return <code>401 Unauthorized</code> with
        <code>"message": "API token expired"</code>. There is no warning
        period — schedule rotation in your client before the deadline.
    </p>

    <h2>Permissions</h2>
    <p>
        For now, every token grants full access to its owner's resources
        (templates, documents, extractions). Scoped tokens (read-only,
        per-resource) are on the roadmap but not yet available.
    </p>
</DocsLayout>
